Unsupervised Learning: Trade&Ahead¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The stock market has consistently proven to be a good place to invest in and save for the future. There are a lot of compelling reasons to invest in stocks. It can help in fighting inflation, create wealth, and also provides some tax benefits. Good steady returns on investments over a long period of time can also grow a lot more than seems possible. Also, thanks to the power of compound interest, the earlier one starts investing, the larger the corpus one can have for retirement. Overall, investing in stocks can help meet life's financial aspirations.

It is important to maintain a diversified portfolio when investing in stocks in order to maximise earnings under any market condition. Having a diversified portfolio tends to yield higher returns and face lower risk by tempering potential losses when the market is down. It is often easy to get lost in a sea of financial metrics to analyze while determining the worth of a stock, and doing the same for a multitude of stocks to identify the right picks for an individual can be a tedious task. By doing a cluster analysis, one can identify stocks that exhibit similar characteristics and ones which exhibit minimum correlation. This will help investors better analyze stocks across different market segments and help protect against risks that could make the portfolio vulnerable to losses.

Objective¶

Trade&Ahead is a financial consultancy firm who provide their customers with personalized investment strategies. They have hired you as a Data Scientist and provided you with data comprising stock price and some financial indicators for a few companies listed under the New York Stock Exchange. They have assigned you the tasks of analyzing the data, grouping the stocks based on the attributes provided, and sharing insights about the characteristics of each group.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Ticker Symbol: An abbreviation used to uniquely identify publicly traded shares of a particular stock on a particular stock market
  • Company: Name of the company
  • GICS Sector: The specific economic sector assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • GICS Sub Industry: The specific sub-industry group assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • Current Price: Current stock price in dollars
  • Price Change: Percentage change in the stock price in 13 weeks
  • Volatility: Standard deviation of the stock price over the past 13 weeks
  • ROE: A measure of financial performance calculated by dividing net income by shareholders' equity (shareholders' equity is equal to a company's assets minus its debt)
  • Cash Ratio: The ratio of a company's total reserves of cash and cash equivalents to its total current liabilities
  • Net Cash Flow: The difference between a company's cash inflows and outflows (in dollars)
  • Net Income: Revenues minus expenses, interest, and taxes (in dollars)
  • Earnings Per Share: Company's net profit divided by the number of common shares it has outstanding (in dollars)
  • Estimated Shares Outstanding: Company's stock currently held by all its shareholders
  • P/E Ratio: Ratio of the company's current stock price to the earnings per share
  • P/B Ratio: Ratio of the company's stock price per share by its book value per share (book value of a company is the net difference between that company's total assets and total liabilities)

def histogram_boxplot(df, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=df, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
       # Add mean
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add median
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )

Create a Function for Creating Barplots for Non-Numerical Variables¶

In [26]:
def labeled_barplot(df, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(df[feature])  # length of the column
    count = df[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=df,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=df[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()

3. How are the different variables correlated with each other?¶

In [30]:
#Find correlation
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 7))
sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot=True, vmin=-1, vmax=1, fmt=".2f", cmap="Spectral")
plt.show()

Observations¶

  • Estimated Shares Outstanding is positively correlated with Net Income at 0.59
    • This may partly reflect the fact that larger firms have more shares and also generate more income in dollars
  • Earnings Per Share is positively correlated with Net Income at 0.56
    • This correlation makes sense intuitively
  • ROE and Earnings Per Share have the largest negative correlation at -0.41
    • This is somewhat counterintuitive
    • ROE was found to always be positive although Net Income is frequently negative
  • Volatility and Earnings Per Share are also found to have a negative correlation at -0.38
    • This may partly reflect that more stable and mature companies have lower volatility and higher earnings in dollars since they are likley larger

    • No outlier treatment will be performed
  • Cash Ratio also has many right hand outliers, however, this can result with low Total Current Liabilities
    • No outlier treatment will be performed
  • Net Cash Flow has many outliers to the left and to the right, however, larger magnitudes are more likely to be associated with large companies
    • The outliers are reasonable as the variable is given in dollars, and not as a percentage
    • No outlier treatment will be performed
  • Net Income has many outliers to the left and to the right, however, larger magnitudes are more likely to be associated with large companies
    • The outliers are reasonable as the variable is given in dollars, and not as a percentage
    • No outlier treatment will be performed
  • Earnings Per Share has a number of outliers to the left and right
    • The outliers are reasonable as EPS varies considerably among companies, as does the number of shares outstanding
    • No outlier treatment will be performed
  • Estimated Shares Outstanding has many outliers to the right
    • The values are reasonable and are likely influenced by company size and the discretion of company management
    • No outlier treatment will be performed
  • P/E Ratio has many outliers to the right
    • This can be a result of low positive earnings
    • However, Net Income was in some cases negative, which would make P/E Ratio also negative
    • RCA should be performed, however, in subsequent analysis the values for P/E Ratio will be assumed to be correct
    • No outlier treatment will be performed
  • P/B Ratio has many outliers to the right and to the left
    • Negative values for P/B Ratio are acceptable when book value per share is negative
    • Outliers may be partly the result of book value of equity that is low in magnitude
    • No outlier treatment will be performed
Although ROE and P/E Ratio only have positive values, these values will be assumed to be correct for subsequent analysis¶
It is otherwise reasonable for all of the variables to have outliers, so no outlier treatment will be performed on any of the variables¶

Distortion Scores with KElbowVisualizer¶

In [42]:
#Check number of clusters from 1 to 8
clusters = range(1, 9)
meanDistortions = []

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1)
    model.fit(subsetScaled)
    prediction = model.predict(k_means_df)
    distortion = (
        sum(np.min(cdist(k_means_df, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1))
        / k_means_df.shape[0]
    )

    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")
plt.title("Selecting k with the Elbow Method", fontsize=20)
plt.show()

In [58]:
# Find combination of distance metric and linkage method that results in the greatest cophenetic correlation

# list of distance metrics
distance_metrics = ['cityblock', 'euclidean', 'chebyshev', 'mahalanobis']

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average'] 

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(hc_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(hc_df))
        print(
            "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm
            
# printing the combination of distance metric and linkage method with the highest cophenetic correlation
print('*'*100)
print(
    "Highest cophenetic correlation is {}, which is obtained with {} distance and {} linkage.".format(
        high_cophenet_corr, high_dm_lm[0].capitalize(), high_dm_lm[1]
    )
)

Insights on Hierarchical Clustering¶

  • Segment 0
    • The segment is by far the largest with 337 out of 340 observed companies
    • Average Price Change is highest but comparable to Segment 1
    • Average Net Cash Flow and average Estimated Shares Outstanding are also highest for this segment
      • Average Estimated Shares Outstanding is comparable to that for Segment 2
  • Segment 1
    • The cluster contains only 1 out of 340 observed companies
      • The company is Priceline.com
    • Average Cash Ratio, average Net Income, and average Earnings Per Share are highest for this segment
  • Segment 2
    • The cluster has 2 out of 340 observed companies
    • Average Volatility, average ROE, average P/E Ratio and average P/B Ratio are greatest for this segment

K-means vs Hierarchical Clustering¶

  • Time to execute
    • Kmeans clustering was shown to take between 0.17 to 0.20 seconds for 2 through 8 clusters
    • Hierarchical clusting was shown to take less time - this is not typical as Kmeans tends to be faster in general
    • This performance could be partially the result of one cluster making up nearly all of the companies analyzed in the hierarchical clustering model
  • Silhouette score for the selected hierarchical cluster model chosen is slightly higher than that of the kmeans cluster model
    • Again, the hierarchical clustering model is dominated by one very large cluster, which seems to be driving this result
      • The score indicates slightly more distinct clusters as a result of having one very large cluster
  • For hiererachical clustering, one cluster makes up 337 out of 340 companies
    • The other two clusters consist of only 1 and 2 companies, respectively
  • For Kmeans clustering, there is still one large cluster with 277
    • However, the other 3 clusters have 11, 27, and 25 companies, respectively
    • Based on better segmentation and other results being comparable or better, Kmeans is the better of the two models
      • Also, having 2 very small clusters from the hierarchical clustering model essentially places all companies into one cluster, defeating the goal of cluster analysis analysis altogether

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

  • From the selected Kmeans model:
    • Cluster 1 contains large companies, many of which could be classified as "blue chip" companies
    • Cluster 2 contains companies with greater Volatility, ROE, and P/E Ratio, which are characteristics of "growth" companies
    • Cluster 3 contains companies with greater Cash Ratio, Net Cash Flow, Earnings Per Share, and P/B Ratio, which are characteristics of "value" companies
      • Additionally, Volatility is low adding further suppport for this cluster comprising "value" companies
  • Younger investors may prefer to have more weight in companies in Cluster 2, as they may be more open to exchanging higher potential long-run returns for greater volatility
    • This may be preferable when retirement is far off, as there is more time to make up potential losses in value
  • Older investors may prefer more weight in Cluster 3, as it contains safer "value" companies
    • This may be preferable when retirement is near
  • In between these two, is Cluster 1 with typically larger companies
    • There is less differentiation in this cluster, but it could be considered to contain companies that do not fit into "value" or "growth" clusters
    • These companies are also quite large in comparison to the other clusters
  • Volatility, Net Cash Flow, and Net Income coule be scaled, prior to Z-score scaling, in order to produce more meaningful insights
    • Volatility could be divided by Price before applying Z-score scaling
    • Net Income and Net Cash Flow could be scaled by some measure of company size
      • One option from this data is the multiply Price by Estimated Shares Outstanding to get Market Value of Equity
      • Market Value of Equity could also be kept in the analysis as a measure of size
  • Also, ideally a root cause analysis could be made to determine why ROE and P/E Ratio are showing only positive values given that Net Income and EPS do have negative values
